TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Paradox of Stretch Goals: Organizations in Pursuit of the Seemingly Impossible
AU  - Sitkin, Sim B.
AU  - See, Kelly E.
AU  - Miller, C. Chet
AU  - Lawless, Michael W.
AU  - Carton, Andrew M.
Y1  - 2011/07/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.0038
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.0038
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 544
EP  - 566
VL  - 36
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We investigate the organizational pursuit of seemingly impossible goals?commonly known as stretch goals. Building from our analysis of the mechanisms through which stretch goals could influence organizational learning and performance, we offer a contingency framework evaluating which organizations are positioned to benefit from such extreme goals and which are most likely to pursue them. We conclude that stretch goals are, paradoxically, most seductive for organizations that can least afford the risks associated with them.
AB  - We investigate the organizational pursuit of seemingly impossible goals?commonly known as stretch goals. Building from our analysis of the mechanisms through which stretch goals could influence organizational learning and performance, we offer a contingency framework evaluating which organizations are positioned to benefit from such extreme goals and which are most likely to pursue them. We conclude that stretch goals are, paradoxically, most seductive for organizations that can least afford the risks associated with them.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.0038
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2008.0038
Y2  - 2026/04/24
