TY  - JOUR
T1  - Managing Joint Production Motivation: The Role of Goal Framing and Governance Mechanisms
AU  - Lindenberg, Siegwart
AU  - Foss, Nicolai J.
Y1  - 2011/07/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2010.0021
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2010.0021
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 500
EP  - 525
VL  - 36
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We contribute to the microfoundations of organizational performance by proffering the construct of joint production motivation. Under such motivational conditions individuals see themselves as part of a joint endeavor, each with his or her own roles and responsibilities; generate shared representations of actions and tasks; cognitively coordinate cooperation; and choose their own behaviors in terms of joint goals. Using goal-framing theory, we explain how motivation for joint production can be managed by cognitive/symbolic management and organizational design.
AB  - We contribute to the microfoundations of organizational performance by proffering the construct of joint production motivation. Under such motivational conditions individuals see themselves as part of a joint endeavor, each with his or her own roles and responsibilities; generate shared representations of actions and tasks; cognitively coordinate cooperation; and choose their own behaviors in terms of joint goals. Using goal-framing theory, we explain how motivation for joint production can be managed by cognitive/symbolic management and organizational design.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2010.0021
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2010.0021
Y2  - 2026/04/24
