TY  - JOUR
T1  - Multiple Team Membership: a Theoretical Model of its Effects on Productivity and Learning for Individuals and Teams
AU  - O'leary, Michael Boyer
AU  - Mortensen, Mark
AU  - Woolley, Anita Williams
Y1  - 2011/07/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.0275
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2009.0275
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 461
EP  - 478
VL  - 36
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Organizations use multiple team membership to enhance individual and team productivity and learning, but this structure creates competing pressures on attention and information, which make it difficult to increase both productivity and learning. Our model describes how the number and variety of multiple team memberships drive different mechanisms, yielding distinct effects. We show how carefully balancing the number and variety of team memberships can enhance both productivity and learning.
AB  - Organizations use multiple team membership to enhance individual and team productivity and learning, but this structure creates competing pressures on attention and information, which make it difficult to increase both productivity and learning. Our model describes how the number and variety of multiple team memberships drive different mechanisms, yielding distinct effects. We show how carefully balancing the number and variety of team memberships can enhance both productivity and learning.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.0275
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2009.0275
